title: For Trade:  Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I have for trade a Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant. This rifle is in very nice shape. Bore is very nice with shine, Stock is a war time stock with the round finger splices not the square kind on post war stocks. This one was built using a 1896 Tula hex reciever model 1891 rifle. Tang has tula hammer and 96r marking on underside. It also has the AZF capture marks from WWI when the Austrians captured the original M91  from the russians. Has the russian eagle on reciever as well with cryptic letters below it. This one was'nt ground by the Finns like alot were. 

Has the 3600 proof, SA in box finnish issue mark as well. Bolt and barrel date match, magazine does not it is a tula and floorplate not marked. And buttplate is not numbered which this is all correct for the M39s as some parts can be and some are not. As well as the force matching the Finns did called Finn Matching. 

This is not a B marked barrel post war put together either.  Barrel has very nice shining bore with excellent crown, cleaning rod is correct one. Stock is very nice.  This one is dated 1943

Shoots excellent and very accurate. Nice war issued M39 in a wartime round finger spliced stock and non B marked barrel. Built on an 1896 russian tula hexagon reciever with its eagle marking and austrian capture marking from WWI. Issued in WWII. Nice little piece of history. 

REDACTED

title: For Sale:  HK Hecklor & Koch PSP 9mm Squeeze Caulker
postcontent:
HK Heckler & Koch PSP 9mm ACP  (almost identical to P7M8)
The P7's spring extractor is contained within the slide, while the fixed ejector is a surface on the slide catch.
The grip of this pistol features a built-in cocking lever activated by gripping the pistol handle. Before the pistol can be fired, this lever must be squeezed. Thus this lever acts as a safety.
The P7 is a German 9mm semi-automatic pistol  produced by Heckler & Koch . It was revealed to the public for the first time in 1976 as the PSP (Polizei-Selbstlade-Pistole—“police self-loading pistol”
The decision to equip West German police with an advanced 9mm service pistol and replace existing 7.65mm-caliber weapons was prompted after the 1972 Munich Olympics MassacreSeries production of the P7 started in 1979. A schematic of the P7's gas-delayed blowback system.  IT HAS A FIXED BARREL WICH HELPS MAKE IT ONE OF THE MOST ACCURATE PISTOLS EVER DESIGNED.
The P7 is a semi-automatic blowback-operated firearm. It features a unique gas-delayed blowback locking system modeled on the Swiss Pistole 47 W+F (Waffenfabrik Bern) prototype pistol[5] (and ultimately on the Barnitzke system first used in the Volkssturmgewehr 1-5[6]), which used gas pressures from the ignited cartridge and fed them through a small port in the barrel (in front of the chamber) to retard the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined—after the bullet has left
The P7 is fed from a single-stack box magazine with a capacity of 8 rounds.
The firearm uses a fixed, polygonal barrel (hexagonal with a 250 mm twist rate) and a fixed notched iron sight with contrast dots that enable shooting in low-level lighting conditions. The pistol is completely ambidextrous and two-handed use is enhanced through the use of a profiled and enlarged trigger guard.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Lee-Enfield No4 Mk2 UF55
postcontent:
Only made for one year, the UF55 is also the last Enfield rifle that was made in Britain.  These post war rifles were built in the Fazakerley factory in 1955 for the British war reserve and got covered with grease, wrapped with paper and put in storage.  The rifles were imported in to the United States in the early 1990's and were sold to the public still in there mummy wraps.  The guns have beech stocks, black "suncorite" baked enamel finish on all the metal parts and brass butt plates.  There is a flip up ladder rear sight with a fine screw adjustment and a cross bolt placed through the receiver for additional strength.

  The rifle I am selling is unwrapped, in very good condition, and has a low serial number.  All the metal parts are scratch free, and the stock has minimal wear from handling and storage.  All the numbers are matching including the ones on the stock and detachable 10 round magazine.  The gun has only been fired a few times so the bore and rifling are both like new. 

  I see these guns selling for about $600 in this condition, and the price I am asking also includes 120 rounds of .303 British, and a bayonet with scabbard and frog.  I would like to keep this gun in the state so I would prefer face to face sales with Vermont residents only.
